Projection Lemma Formal Proof
Lemma Statement
Projection Lemma Let ϕ∈ΨFinal be a Pure Information element (non local, infinitely replicable, meaningfully identical copies). Let P:Ψ→O be an information preserving projection that maps information states to physical objects while preserving semantic identity. Under Ownership Axiom A2 (ownerability requires locatability and isolatability), if ¬Owner(ϕ) then ¬Owner(P(ϕ)). In symbols:
¬Owner(ϕ) ∧ P is information preserving ⟹ ¬Owner(P(ϕ)).
Formal Definitions and Assumptions
Def 1 Pure Information
ϕ∈ΨFinal  ⟺  ϕ is non local and for all n∈N ∃ ϕ1,…,ϕn: ϕ=ϕi (semantic identity).
Def 2 Information Preserving Projection P is information preserving if for any ϕ,ψ,
ϕ=ψ ⇒ P(ϕ) and P(ψ) are semantically identical physical realizations.
Axiom A2 Ownership
Owner(x,p)⇒(Locatable(x)∧Isolatable(x)).
Assumptions
•	A1 Semantic identity is transitive and well defined: if ϕ=ϕ′ and ϕ′=ϕ′′ then ϕ=ϕ′′.
•	A2 Locatability means there exists a measurable location map L assigning a unique spatial region to the object.
•	A3 Isolatable means there exists an operation that, within finite resources, separates the object from other semantically identical instances so that exclusive control is possible.
•	A4 Projection P does not introduce asymmetry that systematically breaks semantic identity across copies unless explicitly specified.
Proof
Step 1 Semantic Multiplicity under Pure Information By Def 1, for any finite set of spatial regions {R1,…,Rm} there exist semantic copies {ϕ1,…,ϕm} with ϕi=ϕ such that each ϕi can be instantiated arbitrarily close to or within each Ri. Thus the information ϕ admits arbitrarily many coexisting semantic instances distributed across space.
Step 2 Projection Produces Multiple Physical Instances Apply the information preserving projection P to each semantic copy. By Def 2 and A1,
ai:=P(ϕi),∀i,
and each ai is semantically identical: ai∼aj for all i,j. Because copies ϕi can be placed in distinct regions, the set {ai} can be realized in distinct spatial regions simultaneously.
Step 3 Failure of Locatability for a Unique Ownerable Target Suppose, for contradiction, that P(ϕ) is ownerable. Then by Axiom A2 there must exist a unique location L(P(ϕ)) and an isolating operation that singles out P(ϕ) from other objects. But from Step 2 there exist arbitrarily many semantically identical ai in distinct regions. Any candidate unique location L∗ cannot be assigned so that it corresponds to a single semantically unique instance, because for any chosen region R containing some aj there exists another ak in R′≠R. Therefore no single-valued location map L can single out a unique semantic instance of P(ϕ). Hence P(ϕ) fails the locatability requirement.
Step 4 Failure of Isolability Isolability requires an operation that, with finite resources, separates the target from all other semantically identical instances so that exclusive control is achievable. Because copies ai are semantically identical and can be instantiated arbitrarily many times and arbitrarily widely, any finite isolation operation applied to one instance does not eliminate the existence of other indistinguishable instances elsewhere. Under A3 and A4, there is no finite procedure that guarantees global uniqueness or exclusivity of control over the semantic content embodied by P(ϕ). Thus isolatability fails.
Step 5 Conclusion by Ownership Axiom From Steps 3 and 4, P(ϕ) is neither locatable nor isolatable. By Axiom A2, locatability and isolatability are necessary for ownerability. Therefore ¬Owner(P(ϕ)). This completes the implication:
¬Owner(ϕ) ∧ P information preserving ⟹ ¬Owner(P(ϕ)).
Corollaries and Remarks
•	Corollary 1 If a projection P intentionally breaks semantic identity (i.e., P(ϕi) are made distinguishable by design), then the lemma does not apply; ownership may become possible. Such a P violates the information preserving assumption.
•	Remark 1 The proof relies on the capacity to instantiate arbitrarily many semantic copies in distinct regions. If physical constraints bound the achievable multiplicity below a threshold that permits isolation, ownerability could be restored; this is captured by the parameterized sensitivity analysis in the main text.
•	Remark 2 The lemma is constructive: to refute it one must present a concrete projection P and a mechanism that (i) preserves semantic identity and (ii) nonetheless yields a locatable and isolatable physical object for which exclusive control is achievable. The counterexample must explicitly identify which assumption A1–A4 it negates.
Limitations and Counterexample Protocol
To challenge the lemma, provide all of the following:
5.	Explicit projection P with formal specification of how semantic identity is mapped to physical degrees of freedom.
6.	Bound on multiplicity showing a provable finite upper bound on realizable semantic copies under physical laws and resource constraints.
7.	Isolation procedure with finite resource proof that separates the projected instance from all other semantically identical instances.
8.	Analysis of which assumption is relaxed and empirical or theoretical justification for that relaxation.
If these items are supplied, the lemma’s premises can be re evaluated and the ownership conclusion re assessed.
Closing Statement
The Projection Lemma formalizes the intuitive claim that an information preserving mapping of a non local, infinitely replicable information state cannot yield a uniquely ownable physical object under the stated ownership axiom. The proof identifies precisely which assumptions must be altered to restore ownerability, making the lemma both rigorous and falsifiable.


 
Compact logical chain
(Pure(ϕ) ∧ InfoPreserving(P))⇒ (∀m∈N ∃a1,…,am ⋀i=1m(ai=P(ϕ)))⇒ (¬∃L such that L assigns a unique spatial region to a single ai) ∧ (¬∃I finite isolation procedure separating ai)⇒ ¬Ownerable(P(ϕ)).
Symbols and English predicates used
•	Pure(φ) : φ is Pure Information (non local and semantically infinitely replicable).
•	InfoPreserving(P) : P is an information preserving projection (semantic identity is preserved under P).
•	P(φ) or a = P(φ) : the physical object a produced by projecting φ.
•	Ownerable(x) : x is ownable; by axiom this means Locatable(x) ∧ Isolatable(x).
•	L : a location map that assigns a unique spatial region to an object.
•	I : an isolation procedure executable with finite resources.
•	Logical connectives: ∀, ∃, ⇒, ∧, ¬ as usual.
Step by step explanation of the chain
5.	Assumption block — leftmost conjunct:
o	We assume Pure(ϕ) and InfoPreserving(P). In plain English: the information state ϕ is non local and admits arbitrarily many semantically identical copies, and the projection P maps information to physical objects without destroying semantic identity.
6.	Multiplicity via projection — first implication:
o	From pure replicability and information preservation we infer that for every finite m we can realize m physical instances a1,…,am with each ai=P(ϕ). This formalizes “arbitrarily many semantically identical physical realizations exist simultaneously.”
7.	Failure of locatability and isolatability — second implication:
o	Because such identical instances can be instantiated in distinct regions, no single location map L can single out a unique semantic instance; hence locatability fails.
o	Because copies are arbitrarily many and distributed, no finite isolation procedure I can guarantee global exclusivity; hence isolatability fails.
8.	Ownership negation by axiom — final implication:
o	By the Ownership axiom (Ownerable ⇒ Locatable ∧ Isolatable), failure of locatability or isolatability implies ¬Ownerable. Therefore the projected object P(ϕ) is not ownable.
One line maximally expanded formula (impactful form)
(Pure(ϕ)∧InfoPreserving(P))⇒(∀m∈N ∃a1,…,am ⋀iai=P(ϕ))⇒(¬∃L unique(L,ai)∧¬∃I finite_isolate(I,ai))⇒¬Ownerable(P(ϕ)).
How to read and reuse this chain
•	Replace Pure, InfoPreserving, Ownerable, unique(L,•), finite_isolate(I,•) with domain specific predicates if you want to test concrete models (e.g., add resource bounds, noise, or non ideal projection).
•	To refute the chain, present a concrete P and bounds showing either (a) multiplicity is physically bounded so that ∃ unique L and finite I hold, or (b) P intentionally breaks semantic identity (violates InfoPreserving). The chain makes explicit which assumption must be denied.

 
