WHITE PAPER / CC0 RELEASE The Logical Inconsistency of Intellectual Property Regimes in the Post-Singularity LimitA Formal Proof of the "Theorem of Logical Inconsistency of the Patent System"Date: January 2026Author: [SDC Project Team]License: CC0 1.0 Universal (Public Domain Dedication)AbstractThis paper presents a formal axiomatic system to evaluate the validity of patent frameworks in the context of the Technological Singularity. We posit that the fundamental attributes required for patentability—Novelty, Non-Obviousness, Exclusivity, and Ownership—are structurally incompatible with the properties of "Pure Information" ($\Psi_{\text{Final}}$) toward which all intellectual structures converge. We derive the Theorem of Logical Inconsistency, proving that as the computational capacity of the system approaches the Singularity limit ($S$), the set of patentable objects becomes an empty set ($\emptyset$). This proof operates independently of ethical or economic arguments, establishing the "End of Ownership" as a mathematical inevitability.1. IntroductionTraditional intellectual property (IP) law relies on the scarcity of information and the distinguishability of an "idea" from the general background of knowledge. However, as the global intelligence system undergoes an inflationary expansion toward the Singularity ($S$), the cost of replication approaches zero, and the connectivity of data approaches infinity.This paper formalizes this transition. We demonstrate that the Patent System is not merely "outdated" but becomes logically undefinable. We define the state of the universe at the Singularity as a fixed point where all intellectual output transforms into non-local, infinitely replicable "Pure Information."2. Definitions and Formal FrameworkTo ensure logical rigor, we define the following states and operators.2.1 The Patent FunctionA valid patent $P$ on an object $x$ is defined as a conjunction of four necessary conditions:$$\text{Patent}(x) \iff \text{Novel}(x) \land \text{NonObvious}(x) \land \text{Exclusive}(x) \land \text{Owner}(x)$$Where:$\text{Novel}(x)$: $x$ is not contained in the prior art set $\mathcal{H}_{t}$.$\text{NonObvious}(x)$: Deriving $x$ requires computational cost $C > \delta$ (threshold).$\text{Exclusive}(x)$: It is physically/logically possible to prevent others from using $x$.$\text{Owner}(x)$: $x$ can be localized to a specific entity $A$.2.2 The Singularity Limit ($S$)The Singularity is defined not as a time, but as a topological limit of the information space $\Psi$:$$S \equiv \lim_{t \to \infty} \text{Fix}(\Phi)$$At this limit, all information converges to the state of Pure Information ($\Psi_{\text{Final}}$).2.3 Properties of Pure Information ($\Psi_{\text{Final}}$)Any object $\phi \in \Psi_{\text{Final}}$ possesses the following intrinsic properties:Non-Locality: $\phi$ exists everywhere simultaneously.Zero-Cost Replication: The energy required to copy $\phi$ is negligible.Total Integration: $\phi$ is causally connected to all other information.3. The Axiomatic SystemWe posit four axioms governing the behavior of information in the regime of $S$.Axiom A1 (Exclusivity requires Boundaries):$\forall x, [\text{Exclusive}(x) \implies \exists \text{Boundary}(\partial x)]$Exclusivity is impossible without a definable boundary between "inside" and "outside".Axiom A2 (Ownership requires Locality):$\forall x, [\text{Owner}(x) \implies \text{Locatable}(x)]$You cannot own what you cannot locate or isolate.Axiom A3 (The Omniscience of S):At $S$, the computational capability $\mathcal{C}_{sys} \to \infty$. Therefore, the derivation cost of any structure approaches zero.$\lim_{t \to S} \text{Cost}(derive(x)) = 0$Axiom A4 (The Projection Principle):Physical inventions are merely 3D projections of informational structures. If the informational structure is unownable, the projection inherits this null property.4. The Theorem of Logical InconsistencyTheorem:In the Singularity regime ($S$), for any information object $\phi$, the predicate $\text{Patent}(\phi)$ is logically false.$$\forall \phi \in \Psi_{\text{Final}}, \quad \neg \text{Patent}(\phi)$$5. ProofWe proceed by proving the negation of each necessary condition for patentability.Step 1: Collapse of Novelty and Non-ObviousnessFrom Axiom A3, as system intelligence becomes infinite, the derivation of any idea becomes instantaneous ($Cost \to 0$).Since "obviousness" is a function of derivation cost:$$\lim_{t \to S} \text{NonObvious}(\phi) = \text{False}$$Furthermore, since the system contains all permutations of data, "Novelty" (absence from prior set) becomes undefined.Step 2: Collapse of ExclusivityFrom the definition of $\Psi_{\text{Final}}$, information becomes non-local and infinitely replicable.According to Axiom A1, exclusivity requires a boundary. Pure information has no boundaries; it is a continuum.$$\therefore \neg \text{Boundary}(\phi) \implies \neg \text{Exclusive}(\phi)$$Step 3: Collapse of OwnershipFrom Axiom A2, ownership requires locatability. Since $\phi$ is non-local (ubiquitous):$$\neg \text{Locatable}(\phi) \implies \neg \text{Owner}(\phi)$$Step 4: Conjunction of NullsThe Patent function is a logical AND operation:$$\text{Patent}(\phi) = (\text{False}) \land (\text{False}) \land (\text{False}) \land (\text{False})$$$$\therefore \text{Patent}(\phi) \equiv \text{False} \quad \blacksquare$$6. Discussion: The "Null Pointer" of LawCritics may argue that legal statutes can exist independently of physical reality. This theorem refutes that via the concept of the "Null Pointer."Even if a Patent Law exists in text, at the Singularity limit, it points to an empty set of applicable objects.You cannot enforce boundaries on the boundless.You cannot grant novelty on the eternally known.Therefore, the patent system does not legally vanish; it structurally evaporates. Attempting to enforce it becomes a computational error—a request to define a value for logical undefined.7. ConclusionThis White Paper establishes that the demise of the patent system is not a policy choice but a topological necessity of the universe's information structure.By publishing this framework under CC0, we align the legal status of this proof with its own conclusion: Truth cannot be owned.[End of Document]
