Abstract
Climate change mitigation increasingly relies on carbon capture, utilization, and storage (CCUS) technologies. However, current research is dominated by technology-specific metrics, proprietary optimizations, and fragmented efficiency definitions.
Here we present a declarative, technology-independent framework defining the upper efficiency limits of carbon fixation at the highest hierarchical level (𝓒⁹), corresponding to cosmic constraints on energy density, entropy reduction, and information ordering.
This work intentionally releases the 𝓒⁹-order efficiency constraints for climate stabilization under CC0, establishing a shared public foundation upon which all future CCUS, artificial photosynthesis, and self-organizing carbon fixation technologies must operate.
________________________________________
1. Motivation
Climate stabilization is not a question of how carbon is fixed, but how efficiently order can be imposed on high-entropy carbon degrees of freedom.
Without a shared, technology-independent definition of efficiency and its limits, future CCUS innovation risks siloization and artificial bottlenecks.
________________________________________
2. Hierarchical Constraint Principle (𝓒ⁿ)
Physical processes are governed by a hierarchy of constraints parameterized by powers of the speed of light.
The highest relevant order for macroscopic entropy manipulation is denoted 𝓒⁹, representing the maximal density of energy, information, and order achievable without violating fundamental physical limits.
________________________________________
3. Definition of Order Quantity
We define the order quantity as:
ΔO≡−ΔSsyskB=ΔI\Delta \mathcal{O} \equiv -\frac{\Delta S_{\text{sys}}}{k_B} = \Delta IΔO≡−kBΔSsys=ΔI 
representing the logarithmic reduction of accessible system states.
This quantity is dimensionless, additive, and independent of material or technological realization.
________________________________________
4. The Three-Pole Principle of Carbon Fixation
Any carbon fixation process decomposes into a linear combination of three irreducible order-generating mechanisms:
1.	A-pole (Endogenous order): self-organization driven by dissipation
2.	B-pole (Exogenous order): externally injected energy and designed pathways
3.	C-pole (Constraint order): informational, topological, or phase-space restriction
This decomposition is complete and non-overlapping.
________________________________________
5. CCUS Efficiency as a Dimensionless Bound
We define CCUS efficiency as a dimensionless ratio:
η≡ΔOOnorm\eta \equiv \frac{\Delta \mathcal{O}}{\mathcal{O}_{\text{norm}}}η≡OnormΔO 
where the normalization scale is fixed by 𝓒⁹-order constraints.
No technological advance can exceed this bound, only redistribute contributions among the three poles.
________________________________________
